ce:section.ce:para:
In 2003, Zhang and Yu firstly designed and fabricated the hierarchical porous titania spheres by a novel sonochemical approach for the enhanced photodegradation of n-pentane in air [51]. Since 2011, there has been an explosive growth in studies on designing and constructing various novel inorganic semiconductor materials with hierarchical superstructures. (Fig. 1
                     ). So far, a myriad of hierarchical porous photocatalysts have been rationally designed and fabricated from the oriented assembly of zero-dimensional (0D, e.g., nanoparticles), one-dimensional (1D, e.g., nanorods, nanowires, nanotubes) and two-dimensional (2D, e.g., nanosheets and nanoplates) nanoscale building blocks (Fig. 2
                     ). The resulting hierarchical porous photocatalysts generally exhibit significantly improved photocatalytic activity due to the combination and integration effects of various strengthening factors. As illustrated in Fig. 2, for instance, a number of novel hierarchical photocatalysts, such as core-shell [52–60], hollow [61–70], yolk-shell (or sphere-in-shell) [71–74] multi-layered microcube [75], hollow boxes [76] and urchin-like micro/nanostructures [77–82] could be constructed by using various kinds of nanoscale building blocks. More recently, a number of mesocrystalline superparticles or supercrystals have been successfully designed and fabricated through self-assembly of 0D nanocrystals [83–86] which may provide a promising strategy to construct anisotropic superstructures by hierarchical self-assembly nanotechnology for photocatalysis applications. Furthermore, branched 1D hierarchical nanostructures [87–92], 1D micro/nanotubes [93,94], dendritic hierarchical photocatalysts [95–99] and 1D-2D hybrids [100–106] also exhibit further improved photocatalytic activities due to the formation of secondary and tertiary branches. More interestingly, a variety of three-dimensional (3D) hierarchical microspheres with exposed facets, multi-shells or hollow structures [61,67,68,107–119], could be successfully fabricated by the self-assembly of 2D ultrathin nanosheeets and nanoplates or 1D nanorods/nanowires, which have been demonstrated to be the most widely studied photocatalysts.

So far, the Z-scheme photocatalysts can be classified into three types (Fig. 12
                        ): (1) traditional liquid-phase Z-scheme photocatalysts (first generation); (2) all-solid-state Z-scheme photocatalysts (second generation), using an electron conductor (such as Au, Ag nanoparticles, carbon); and (3) direct Z-scheme photocatalysts (the current third generation) [186,258]. Clearly, the traditional liquid-phase Z-scheme photocatalysts are significantly restricted by the undesirable redox mediator-induced back reactions, light-shielding effect and unstable redox mediators, whereas the all-solid-state Z-scheme photocatalysts are affected by the expensive noble-metal electron mediators and the shielding effect [186,258]. Luckily, the direct Z-scheme photocatalysts not only retain the advantages of the first and second generation Z-scheme photocatalysts, including improved electron–hole separation efficiency and optimized redox potential, but also have the additional advantages of greatly reduced construction cost and minimized light-shielding effect (Fig. 13
                        ) [258], thus leading to their wide studies for various photocatalytic applications [129,196,259–267].

In fact, the photocatalytic reactions mainly occur on the surface of semiconductors. Accordingly, optimizing the surface properties play crucial roles in boosting the photocatalytic activity. So far, various surface modification strategies have been reported. The typical examples for surface modification of hierarchical photocatalysts are summarized in Table 2
                     . In this section, we will highlight four typical modification strategies, namely, loading suitable cocatalysts, exposing reactive facets, introducing defects/heteroatoms, and adding photosensitizers (Fig. 33
                     ).

Furthermore, the tuned photocatalytic selectivity will also be highlighted to further extend the applications of hierarchical photocatalysts with the highly reactive facets. For instance, the hollow TiO2 microspheres (HTS) with exposed ca. 20% (0 0 1) facets were found to display adjustable photocatalytic selectivity in degrading azo dyes (Fig. 39
                        A–D) [443]. The photodegradation rate of MV is much slower than that of MO without modifying HTS, whereas the photodegradation rate of MV is faster than that of MO after NaOH washing of the HTS [443]. Liu demonstrated that exposing more (0 0 1) facets resulted in tuning adsorption selectivity of HTS for azo dyes (Fig. 39E–H). In addition, it was found that the tunable photocatalytic selectivity in decomposing MB and MO could be achieved through the simple surface modification of hollow TiO2 spherical photocatalysts [368]. The surface-bonded fluoride and hydroxyl groups of hollow TiO2 microspheres could achieve the selective decomposition of MO and MB, respectively (Fig. 40
                        ) [368]. In future, it is expected that more and more hierarchical photocatalysts with the highly reactive facets and tuned photocatalytic selectivity could be constructed for the photodegradation and photoreduction of CO2 into solar fuels. Moreover, the loading of single or dual cocatalysts on the exposed facets of hierarchical photocatalysts are also encouraged to further boost the photoactivity [442].
